# HTML Accessibility

## Requirement

All HTML files SHALL be accessible and SHALL follow WCAG 2.1 Level AA guidelines.

## Image Alt Attributes

All `<img>` elements SHALL include an `alt` attribute:

```html
<img src="photo.jpg" alt="Description of the image">
```

- Decorative images SHALL use empty alt text: `alt=""`
- Informative images SHALL have descriptive alt text
- Alt text SHALL accurately describe the image content and function

## Heading Hierarchy

HTML files SHALL maintain proper heading hierarchy:

- There SHALL be exactly one `<h1>` element per page
- Headings SHALL NOT skip levels (e.g., h1 → h3 without h2)
- Heading hierarchy SHALL be logical: h1 → h2 → h3 → h4 → h5 → h6

Example of proper hierarchy:

```html
<h1>Main Page Title</h1>
  <h2>Section Title</h2>
    <h3>Subsection Title</h3>
  <h2>Another Section</h2>
```

## Form Labels

All form input elements SHALL be associated with labels:

```html
<label for="username">Username:</label>
<input type="text" id="username" name="username">
```

Or using implicit association:

```html
<label>
  Username:
  <input type="text" name="username">
</label>
```

## ARIA Attributes

ARIA attributes SHALL be used when semantic HTML is insufficient:

- Use `aria-label` when text is not visible but needed for screen readers
- Use `aria-labelledby` to reference visible text
- Use `aria-describedby` for additional descriptions
- Use `role` attributes when semantic HTML cannot express the purpose

ARIA attributes SHALL NOT be used when semantic HTML can express the same meaning.

## Keyboard Navigation

All interactive elements SHALL be keyboard accessible:

- Links and buttons SHALL be focusable
- Focus indicators SHALL be visible
- Tab order SHALL be logical
- Interactive elements SHALL have keyboard event handlers if they have mouse event handlers

## Color Contrast

Text SHALL meet WCAG 2.1 Level AA contrast requirements:

- Normal text: minimum 4.5:1 contrast ratio
- Large text (18pt+ or 14pt+ bold): minimum 3:1 contrast ratio

Color SHALL NOT be the only means of conveying information.

## Semantic HTML

HTML files SHALL use semantic HTML elements to improve accessibility:

- Use `<button>` for buttons, not `<div>` or `<span>` with click handlers
- Use `<nav>` for navigation
- Use proper form elements (`<input>`, `<select>`, `<textarea>`)
- Use `<label>` for form labels

## Focus Management

Interactive elements SHALL manage focus appropriately:

- Focus SHALL be visible and clear
- Focus order SHALL be logical
- Focus SHALL not be trapped unless necessary (modals, etc.)
